post_text:
September is Attendance Awareness Month! Even during remote learning, attendance is vital to student success! https://www.kent.k12.wa.us/Attendance

We all wish we could be learning from our buildings, but while we're remote learning here are some tips to help make sure your child is ready for learning each day:
- Find a spot free from distractions for them to focus
- Create a daily routine
- Check in with your child's teacher and make sure to let them know if you have technical issues

During remote learning, students are marked present if they participate in live learning activities (Teams meetings, emails, phone calls, etc.) or are posting, share, or responding to learning (Canvas, turning in assignments, etc.). If you have questions about your student's attendance please reach out to their teacher or school.

Exciting news! Today the US Department of Agriculture (USDA) announced they will extend the summer meal program through December 31, 2020, depending on federal funding! üéâ

We are still waiting for further guidance from the Office of Superintendent of Public Instruction (OSPI), but to ensure all of our students have the nutrition they need to begin remote learning this week, we are offering free meals to all of our students on *WEDNESDAY*, September 2 from 2-4 p.m. Learn more about how this helps us continue to support our students and families: https://bit.ly/3hOELOg

Since schools closed in March due to the ongoing Covid-19 pandemic, we have served more than 974,400 meals. Thank you to all of the staff and volunteers who have made this possible!

post_text:
Back To School Tip 4Ô∏è‚É£: Prepare For Remote Learning Success

Remote learning this fall will look different than last spring. Students will engage in instruction through a Learning Management System (Canvas) and a virtual meeting platform (Microsoft Teams). Teachers may also use emails, phone conferences, video conferencing, independent learning, and supplemental learning applications to support remote learning.

Weekly schedules will go out on Fridays for the following week in Canvas so you and your child can plan for the week ahead.

If you haven't received your student's teacher assignment or detailed class schedule already, it will be coming from your school before the start of school. Please continue to check your email (and spam/junk folder) for updates.

Learn more about what to expect by reading through our reopening plan: https://www.kent.k12.wa.us/ReopeningPlan

Ready Set Play Covington is feeling pumped with Covington Chamber Of Commerce - Covington, WA and 2 others at Covington Community Park.
August 3 at 7:31 AM ¬∑ Covington, WA ¬∑

Hooray! It‚Äôs grand opening day for Ready Set Play!

We are so excited to kick off this new eight week program to get kiddos active, creative, thinking and playing! We have designed this season‚Äôs activities to be socially safe and collecting tags from our sponsor locations all follow safety guidelines.

There are 24 opportunities to earn Brag Tags between Aug. 3 and Sept. 30, with those kiddos who collect all 24 on their official program lanyard provided by MultiCare earning a grand prize which includes 10 free swims at the Covington Aquatic Center when they fully reopen!

You can stop by Covington Community Park today (or Monday through Thursday of this week) from 12-4 p.m. to pick up a free official lanyard. If you cant make it, several of our Brag Tag locations will also have them available throughout the eight weeks. Be sure to visit www.covingtonwa.gov/readysetplay for program details and link to a listing of all activities and any special instructions.

post_text: This week, our KSD Back to School Task Force focused on a plan for remote learning for all students. Remote learning will be available in the event school buildings remain closed in the fall, or should they close abruptly due to a resurgence of COVID-19. Remote learning in 2020-21 will be high-quality and consistently provided with more explicit expectations and accountability for instruction and assignments. Learning opportunities and supports for families on the districtwide learning management system, supplemental learning applications, and student-teacher communication platform will be provided. Read the full update, and visit our website for more about the reopening plan, including answers to frequently asked questions. https://bit.ly/2ZDKmQT #KSDCommunity

post_text: Our Back to School Task Force has been hard at work preparing for several scenarios related to reopening our buildings for the 2020-21 school year, including actively developing a hybrid learning model with students attending school in-person regularly, but not daily. Next week all KSD families will be asked to complete a readiness survey. This survey will help us know more precisely how many families are comfortable having students return to school buildings this fall, even in a part-time status. Learn more by reading today‚Äôs full update sent via email, mobile app and on our website. As guidance continues to change, we will all need to continue to be agile and patient in the coming weeks. In the meantime, we encourage everyone to be mindful of key preventive measures, including wearing face coverings and washing your hands thoroughly. Please help us reopen our schools and show us your mask on social media! #MASKUP #SHOWUSYOURMASK #KSDCommunity https://bit.ly/3iUQEDA

June 12 at 4:08 PM ¬∑

After serving on #TeamKSD415 for 41 years, Peggy Houden is retiring. She works at Emerald Park Elementary as a first-grade teacher. Prior to teaching at Emerald Park, she taught first-grade at Covington Elementary. Peggy had a keen interest in child development and learning/memory theory when she was at the University of Illinois. She continued her education at the University of Washington and was a leader in the field of Early Childhood Special Education.

Peggy had the opportunity to help open Emerald Park and was surrounded by dedicated staff who worked well together to build an amazing school culture and community. She said she truly found a home at that school. Over the years, Peggy learned teaching is both an art and a science, and a truly great teacher is a master of both. She plans to travel with her husband, Kevin, when the world becomes a safer place again.

Please join us in celebrating Peggy and all of our #TeamKSD415 Retirees! https://www.kent.k12.wa.us/Retirees

"Completing my National Boards was such a great experience!" Sunrise Elementary School Teacher Shannon Bolton said. "It really pushed me to take a closer look at my teaching and stretched myself to become a better teacher. I learned how to look closely at my teaching strategies and the impact they have on student learning. It was very challenging, but well worth it. I am very proud of this accomplishment."

Join us in celebrating our incredible teachers who earned their National Board Certification by meeting high standards through study, expert evaluation, self-assessment, and peer review. Learn more and see the full list of recipients on our website: https://bit.ly/3cAhwUI

Great news! Starting WEDNESDAY, MAY 27, we're supporting the Pacific Coast Fruit Company in distributing free USDA Farmers to Families Boxes to our families!

Three different boxes are available to choose from and will be available at locations across our district every Wednesday from 11 a.m. to 12:30 p.m.!

Please note: These are different than our free school meals boxes available on Mondays. These boxes are prepackaged by Pacific Coast Fruit and weigh about 25 pounds each. We recommend bringing a wagon, carriage, or several bags to help carry the box if you are walking to a site.

When Kentridge Senior Alexis Jordan and her classmates were planning for the final months of their senior year, they didn't know a pandemic would force them to miss out on milestones they'd been dreaming of for years.

"A lot of us are extremely disappointed that we do not get the wonderful experiences that we‚Äôve been waiting so long for," Alexis said. "I appreciate everything that parents, teachers, and staff have done so far to ensure our final year at KR doesn‚Äôt end on a bad note."

Alexis and other ABS Senators decided to celebrate the Class of 2020's achievements virtually by creating a series of videos sharing their future plans. We will share these videos throughout these final weeks of our school year and you can help celebrate these incredible students by liking, commenting, and sharing!

Whether it‚Äôs military service, trade school, college, or career, the future is bright for all of our graduating seniors! üéìüéâ

FREE MEALS UPDATE:
To continue to serve our families free meals as safely as possible, we'll be providing boxes with free meals for the week on Mondays starting April 13. We've also added select bus stops!

Please visit one of our drive-through or walk-up sites to pick up a box of meals for each child in your household. Each box has 5 breakfasts and 5 lunches with info. on how to store and prepare the food inside.

Learn more and find a site near you on our website at http://www.kent.k12.wa.us/ClosureMeals.

post_text:
Thank you for your support and patience as we navigate this first week of building closures. Together with our leaders we continue unpacking the mandates and guidelines around this unprecedented health crisis as we make and implement decisions that best support our students, families, and our staff.
We have come to agreement on one major priority set by the Office of the Superintendent of Public Instruction which is childcare for school-age children of first responders and health care workers.
We are also happy to share that this means an expansion of one additional meal service location for children in our KSD community beginning Monday, March 23. Details regarding the childcare and the meal service offerings are available via email and our website.
Thank you for your patience, for choosing kindness, extending grace, and assuming positive intent during this time. We will continue to provide information and updates as appropriate. Take care of each other! https://bit.ly/3bawzUR #KSDCommunity

As of 4 p.m. Monday, March 9, 2020, we have no confirmed cases of COVID-19 in our schools. Our Executive Leadership Team continues to meet twice daily to address the concerns and needs of our students and staff. The district is actively engaging in contingency planning for the possibility of extended school closures. We continue to answer your questions and we are frequently updating our FAQ web page.
Last week at a press conference Seattle King County Public Health reiterated that closing schools and districts when there has not been a confirmed case in a student or staff member is not currently recommended by them or the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. We will continue to take direction from the Seattle King County Public Health on school closures. If their directions change, and targeted or widespread school closures are implemented, we will let you know quickly through our KSD communication channels.
We continue to act out of an abundance of caution to protect everyone‚Äôs health and wellbeing. http://bit.ly/39OizQF

Kentwood High School and Covington Elementary School will be closed on Tuesday, March 3, 2020, as we complete the thorough cleaning and disinfecting of both schools in alignment with the Center for Disease Control standards.
The safety of our students and staff is our first priority. We are adhering to our standard cleaning practices that include hospital-grade disinfectant cleaner in all KSD schools and facilities. Cleaning and disinfection of surfaces will continue throughout our schools and on our buses per the standard procedures for infection prevention.
We cannot stress enough the importance of staying home when sick, washing hands frequently, avoiding touching one‚Äôs face.
During this time of heightened anxiety, our community values may be tested. We need to continue to demonstrate compassion and care as we navigate this global health situation. Please visit the Washington State Department of Health website for the most accurate and up to date information.

post_text:
Out of an abundance of caution, Kentwood High School and Covington Elementary School are closed on Monday, March 2, 2020. One KSD family with connections to both schools has an adult family member with flu-like symptoms and is awaiting testing for the Coronavirus (COVID-19). We have mobilized our custodial staff to begin thoroughly cleaning and disinfecting both schools. This may take more than one day to complete, school closure decisions for March 3 will be announced by 5pm on Monday, March 2.
We will also be using tomorrow‚Äôs closures to communicate with the families of those students and staff that the students may have come into contact with last week.
The safety of our students and staff is our first priority. Please visit our website or the Washington State department of Health for more information about the Coronavirus. We will continue to monitor the situation and update you as we have more information.

shared_text:
Park Orchard Elementary
February 25 at 4:36 PM ¬∑

During Conference week the PTSA held its annual book fair. Thanks to Scholastic's eWallet system (and a great idea by our Librarian) some funds were donated to buy books for students that didn't have the funds to make a purchase. Our Teacher of the Year nominee, Mr. Parsons, took the idea and ran with it managing to raise over a $1000 in donations for his class to buy books. Mr. Parsons asked for the students who were willing to buy a little something for one of the kindergarten classes and over two thirds of the class did. Here are some pictures of those lucky sixth graders and the day they took their purchases to kindergarten. #KSDProud #PandaPride

We've been recognized as one of the top-performing districts in the state for signing up 79% of eligible students for the College Bound Scholarship, a program that provides an early commitment of state financial aid to eligible students who sign up in middle school and fulfill the scholarship pledge. http://bit.ly/39sotX0

Cedar Heights, Kent Mountain View Academy, Mattson, Meridian, and Mill Creek middle schools all received gold star awards for exceeding the state sign-up rate.

Thank you to our staff, families, and community for supporting our goal of preparing all students to be college and career reading by raising the academic and social learning bar and closing the gaps to student achievement and college completion!

Congratulations Meeker Cheer! Over the weekend, they earned 3 state titles!
"They worked incredibly hard on their routines and took home 1st place in Traditional, Game Day, and Stomp at the WSCCA State Championships!" Cheer Coach Lisa Cabalquinto told us with pride. This is their program's 9th state title.
shared_text:
Meeker Cheer
January 27 at 7:42 AM ¬∑

NINE x STATE CHAMPIONS!

Congratulations to the Meeker Cheerleaders, past and present, who have contributed to our program's success! With your dedication, commitment, and hard work, we've earned NINE State Titles including 4x defending Traditional State Champions, 3x defending Stomp State Champions.

It's hard to get to the top and even more difficult to stay there but we've made it! Remember, it's not always easy but it's always worth it.

Thank you to all of the cheerleaders, partners, Meeker staff who have supported us along the way. We wouldn't be here without you!
